data.content:
Blockchain	IU-SmartCert
decentralization, security
IU-SmartCert utilizes Blockchain technology to ensure the secure management and selective disclosure of educational credentials.

Issuer	Learner
credential issuance, selective disclosure
Issuers issue digital credentials to learners, who then have the ability to selectively disclose their credential components to relying parties as needed.

Learner	Relying Party
verification process, interaction
Learners present selected credential components from their issued credentials to relying parties for verification purposes.

Ethereum	IU-SmartCert
smart contract deployment, transparency
IU-SmartCert deploys its operations on the Ethereum blockchain to leverage smart contracts for secure and transparent credential management.

Credential Schema	Issuer
schema definition, flexibility
Issuers define a Credential Schema for each program to structure credentials into mandatory and optional components in IU-SmartCert.

Learner	Mandatory Component
disclosure requirement, validation
The Mandatory Component must be disclosed by the Learner to every Relying Party, containing essential information for credential validation.

Learner	Optional Components
selective disclosure, privacy
Learners can select from Optional Components to disclose selectively when presenting credentials to a Relying Party, enhancing privacy and relevance.

Ethereum Blockchain	IU-SmartCert
data publishing, security
IU-SmartCert publishes data to the Ethereum blockchain for secure and independent validation of digital credentials.

Digital Credentials	Merkle Tree
credential organization, cryptographic validation
A Merkle tree is constructed using the schema and fingerprints of each credential in IU-SmartCert to organize and validate digital credentials efficiently.

Ethereum Blockchain	Smart Contract
independent verification, blockchain technology
Smart contracts on the Ethereum blockchain store hash values of Merkle tree roots for credential validation, facilitating independent verification by a relying party without issuer contact.

Digital Credentials	Issuer
credential generation, component provision
The issuer generates and provides components of digital credentials in IU-SmartCert for learner validation.

Digital Credential	Learner
credential receipt, education verification
A learner receives a digital credential from the institution via IU-SmartCert upon program completion.

Certificate Authority (CA)	Issuer
identity verification, digital signature authentication
The Certificate Authority issues X.509 certificates to verify and bind the identity of issuers in IU-SmartCert.

Issuer	X.509 Certificate
authentication, certification authority<SEP>digital trust, identity binding
An X.509 certificate digitally signed by a CA confirms the legitimacy and originality of an issuer's credentials in IU-SmartCert.<SEP>The X.509 certificate is used to verify the issuer's information, including their signature, as part of credential validation.

CA (Certification Authority)	X.509 certificate
verification, digital signature
The CA verifies issuer identity, writes it into an X.509 certificate, and digitally signs it to ensure credential originality.

Ethereum account	IU-SmartCert
endorsement, blockchain integration
Issuers endorse their Ethereum accounts using the private key of the X.509 certificate as part of publishing credentials in IU-SmartCert.

Revocation list	Smart contract
credential management, revocation process
The smart contract stores a revocation list that allows issuers to mark credential components as revoked and maintain the validity status.

Merkle tree	Receipt
data integrity, selective disclosure
A Merkle tree is used within receipts to establish proofs of existence for credential components, facilitating authentication without exposing all details.

Ethereum Network	IU-SmartCert
verification process, blockchain technology
The Ethereum network is utilized by IU-SmartCert for verifying credentials, including checking smart contract validity and revocations.

Issuer's Information	X.509 Certificate
authentication, digital security
Issuerâ€™s information is validated using an X.509 certificate, which provides authentication details such as the issuer's signature.

Credential	Merkle Tree
data integrity, blockchain verification
Credentials are verified against a Merkle tree to confirm their integrity and association with the correct set of data on Ethereum blockchain.

Digital Signature	Issuer
authentication, credential issuance
The issuer signs credentials with a digital signature to authenticate them within IU-SmartCert's verification process.

Relying Party	Smart Contract
verification process, blockchain access
A relying party accesses the smart contract on Ethereum to verify issuer information and check for revoked credentials.

Receipt	Relying Party
data verification, independence from issuer
The receipt provides the necessary data for a relying party to independently verify a credential without involving the issuer.

Merkle Tree	Smart Contract
data integrity, blockchain verification
The smart contract utilizes the Merkle tree structure on Ethereum to ensure credentials are part of a valid set published on the blockchain.
